 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 狄, a term referring to the tribes in ancient northern China: (i) from Di (狄), the name of an ancient state (thought to have been located in Hebei or Shandong province), which was granted to Xiao Bo or Kao Bo by King Cheng of Zhou (reigned 1042–1021  BC ). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Ku Di (庫狄) family during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iii) traced back to other minority ethnic groups in ancient northwestern China.","Mandarin form of the Chinese surname 邸, meaning ‘official residence’ in Chinese: (i) from placename Di (邸), the name of a county (unidentified location). (ii) said to be borne by some descendants of Kujula Kadphises (called 丘就郤 or 邸就郤 in Chinese, 30–<i>c.</i> 80  AD ), founder of the Kushan Empire (one branch of the Yuezhi people originating from western China) located in Central Asia during the Eastern Han dynasty (25–220  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Chi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Young, Dong, Yun, Cheng, Jae, Yong, Cheng Chung, Chi, Chun, Duk, Fang, Feng.  Korean Chung, Chong, Jae Hong, Moon, Myong, Pong, Shen, Yoo, Byung, Chang, Chol, Chong Hun.  Southeast Asian Phi, Hung, Ly, Tu, Denh, Do Van, Duong, Hao, Kieu, Mui, Nga, Phat.","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 池, meaning ‘moat’ in ancient Chinese: (i) acquired as a surname by people who lived beside a moat. (ii) from Chi (池), said to be the name of an ancient state (of unknown location and period). (iii) from the personal name Chi (池), personal name of a son of an official in the state of Qin during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin and Cantonese form of the surname 遲, meaning ‘late’ in Chinese: (i) borne by descendants of Chi Ren (遲任), a person who lived during the Shang dynasty (1600–1046  BC ). (ii) shortened form of the Chinese compound surname Yu-Chi (尉遲), originally the name of a tribe from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China. (iii) from the second element of the personal name Zi Chi (子遲), style name of Fan Xu, a student of Confucius (551–479  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Salerno,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Sal, Salvatore, Pasquale, Carmine, Rocco, Aldo, Nunzio, Enrico, Francesco, Gaspare.","Italian (southern): habitational name from the city of Salerno in Campania."],"variants":[{"name":"Salierno","meanings":["Italian (mainly Campania): variant with metaphony of   Salerno  ."]}]},{"name":"Count","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>counte</i> ‘count’ (Old French <i>conte</i>, from Latin <i>comes</i>, <i>comitem</i>); a title of French and Norman nobility, ranking as equivalent to English   Earl  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Earl","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>e(o)rl</i> ‘earl’, a traditional English title of nobility equivalent in rank to French and Norman   Count  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: possibly a metonymic occupational name for a fisherman, from <i>orfe</i>, a species of freshwater fish. Alternatively, a habitational name from Urff near Kassel, formerly Orpha."],"variants":[{"name":"Orff","meanings":["German: variant of   Orf  ."]}]},{"name":"Capaccio","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Rosario, Vito, Luigi, Matteo, Salvatore, Vita.","Italian: habitational name from Capàccio in Salerno province."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Pandolfo","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Mario, Giuseppe, Salvatore, Antonio, Carmine, Dino, Elio, Enrico, Luigi, Massimo, Nicola, Nino.","Italian (Campania and Tuscany): from the personal name <i>Pandolfo</i>, from Langobardic <i>Pandulf</i>, composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>bandwo-</i> ‘banner’ + <i>wulfa</i> ‘wolf’."],"variants":[{"name":"Pandolfi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Aldo, Dante, Alfonso, Alfonzo, Antonio, Arsenio, Carmela, Domenic, Francesco, Livio, Luca, Orlando, Rafael, Renato, Rico, Rocco, Santi, Siro.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Pandolfo  ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Don Pandolfo di Salerno, Count of Capaccio was born about 1014, in Capaccio, Salerno, Campania, Italy, his father, Guaimar III le Toscan de Salerne, was 27 and his mother, Gaitelgrima de Bénévent, was 23. He had at least 5 sons with Teodora, dei Palatini de Tusculo. He died on 3 June 1052, at the age of 39."},"et":{"about 1014–3 June 1052":"umbes 1014–3. juuni 1052","1008–Male":"1008–Surnud","1010–1052":"1010–1052","1013–1052":"1013–1052","1014–1052":"1014–1052","1025–Female":"1025–Surnud","1020–Female":"1020–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1062–1121":"1062–1121","–1119":"–1119","–Male":"Surnud","0988–1027":"0988–1027","0992–1031":"0992–1031","1121":"1121","1010":"1010","1031":"1031","1020":"1020","@#DJULIAN@ 07 JAN 1031":"7. jaanuar 1031","1052":"1052","1062":"1062","07 JAN 1027":"7. jaanuar 1027","1008":"1008","1027":"1027","0992":"0992","1025":"1025","1014":"1014","1013":"1013","about 1014":"umbes 1014","3 June 1052":"3. juuni 1052","0988":"0988","1119":"1119","Salerne, Salerne, Campanie, Italie":"Itaalia","Campania, Capaccio, Salerno, Italy":"Capaccio, Salerno, Campania, Itaalia"},"fi":{"about 1014–3 June 1052":"noin 1014–3. kesäkuuta 1052","1008–Male":"1008–Kuollut","1010–1052":"1010–1052","1013–1052":"1013–1052","1014–1052":"1014–1052","1025–Female":"1025–Kuollut","1020–Female":"1020–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1062–1121":"1062–1121","–1119":"–1119","–Male":"Kuollut","0988–1027":"0